"host_acceptance_rate", "host_is_superhost", "neighbourhood_cleansed", "neighbourhood_group_cleansed", "latitude", "longitude", "room_type", "accommodates", "bedrooms", "beds", "amenities", "price", ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=4} ``` {.python .cell-code} hi_listings.info() ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` RangeIndex: 30760 entries, 0 to 30759 Data columns (total 19 columns): # Column Non-Null Count Dtype --- ------ -------------- ----- 0 id 30760 non-null int64 1 host_name 30758 non-null object 2 host_acceptance_rate 29485 non-null object 3 host_is_superhost 30680 non-null object 4 neighbourhood_cleansed 30760 non-null object 5 neighbourhood_group_cleansed 30760 non-null object 6 latitude 30760 non-null float64 7 longitude 30760 non-null float64 8 room_type 30760 non-null object 9 accommodates 30760 non-null int64 10 bedrooms 26865 non-null float64 11 beds 30319 non-null float64 12 amenities 30760 non-null object 13 price 30760 non-null object 14 minimum_nights 30760 non-null int64 15 maximum_nights 30760 non-null int64 16 has_availability 30760 non-null object 17 review_scores_rating 23967 non-null float64 18 instant_bookable 30760 non-null object dtypes: float64(5), int64(4), object(10) memory usage: 4.5+ MB ``` ::: ::: ### Cleaning the lisings dataframe #### The `amenities` column The `amenities` column contains strings that look like a list! ::: {.cell execution_count=5} ``` {.python .cell-code} hi_listings["amenities"].head() ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=5} ``` 0 ["Microwave", "Coffee maker", "Hair dryer", "T... 1 ["Microwave", "Free parking on premises", "Hai... 2 ["Lockbox", "Free street parking", "TV", "Smok... 3 ["Baking sheet", "Toaster", "Ethernet connecti... 4 ["Hair dryer", "Essentials", "Hangers", "Shamp... Name: amenities, dtype: object ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=6} ``` {.python .cell-code} type(hi_listings.loc[0, "amenities"]) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=6} ``` str ``` ::: ::: Transforming the column values to list and counting the number of elements in each list! I'm actualy interested in the number of amenities! ::: {.cell execution_count=7} ``` {.python .cell-code} hi_listings["amenities"] = hi_listings["amenities"].transform(ast.literal_eval).str.len() hi_listings["amenities"].head() ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=7} ``` 0 9 1 19 2 23 3 65 4 5 Name: amenities, dtype: int64 ``` ::: ::: #### The `host_acceptance_rate` column ::: {.cell execution_count=8} ``` {.python .cell-code} hi_listings["host_acceptance_rate"].head(3) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=8} ``` 0 100% 1 100% 2 100% Name: host_acceptance_rate, dtype: object ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=9} ``` {.python .cell-code} hi_listings["host_acceptance_rate"] = ( hi_listings["host_acceptance_rate"] .replace('%', '', regex=True) .astype('float') .multiply(0.01) ) hi_listings["host_acceptance_rate"].head(3) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=9} ``` 0 1.00 1 1.00 2 1.00 Name: host_acceptance_rate, dtype: float64 ``` ::: ::: #### The `price` column ::: {.cell execution_count=10} ``` {.python .cell-code} hi_listings["price"].head(3) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=10} ``` 0 $103.00 1 $542.00 2 $109.00 Name: price, dtype: object ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=11} ``` {.python .cell-code} hi_listings["price"] = ( hi_listings["price"] .str.replace('$', '', regex=True) .str.replace(',', '', regex=True) .astype('float') ) hi_listings["price"].head(3) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=11} ``` 0 103.00 1 542.00 2 109.00 Name: price, dtype: float64 ``` ::: ::: #### The columns `host_is_superhost`, `has_availability`, and `instant_bookable` They are all boolean columns in the sense that their data represents true and false values, but currently are recognized as objects. ::: {.cell execution_count=12} ``` {.python .cell-code} hi_listings[["host_is_superhost", "has_availability", "instant_bookable"]].head(3) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=12} ```{=html}
host_is_superhost has_availability instant_bookable
0 f t t
1 t t t
2 f t t
``` ::: ::: The letters in these columns (t and f) are written as strings and not as boolean data types. This means we need to replace our string values with the boolean equivalent dtype. Change the columns host_is_superhost, instant_bookable, and has_availability into a boolean data type for better data processing. ::: {.cell execution_count=13} ``` {.python .cell-code} hi_listings[["host_is_superhost", "has_availability", "instant_bookable"]] = ( hi_listings[["host_is_superhost", "has_availability", "instant_bookable"]] .replace({"f": False, "t": True}) .astype('bool') ) hi_listings[["host_is_superhost", "has_availability", "instant_bookable"]].head(3) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=13} ```{=html}
host_is_superhost has_availability instant_bookable
0 False True True
1 True True True
2 False True True
``` ::: ::: ### Renaming columns The following column names need to be changed: - `price` into `price_US$` - `neighbourhood_cleansed` into `neighbourhood` - `neighbourhood_group_cleansed` into `neighbourhood_group` ::: {.cell execution_count=14} ``` {.python .cell-code} hi_listings = hi_listings.rename( columns={ "price": "price_US$", "neighbourhood_cleansed": "neighbourhood", "neighbourhood_group_cleansed": "neighbourhood_group" } ) ``` ::: #### Categorical columns Taking a closer look at the `neighbourhood`, `neighbourhood_group`, and `room_type` columns reveals that these columns are assigned an **object dtype**. We want them to be a **category** dtype. ::: {.cell execution_count=15} ``` {.python .cell-code} hi_listings[["neighbourhood", "neighbourhood_group", "room_type"]] = ( hi_listings[["neighbourhood", "neighbourhood_group", "room_type"]] .astype('category') ) ``` ::: #### Missing Values ::: {.cell execution_count=16} ``` {.python .cell-code} hi_listings.isnull().sum() ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=16} ``` id 0 host_name 2 host_acceptance_rate 1275 host_is_superhost 0 neighbourhood 0 neighbourhood_group 0 latitude 0 longitude 0 room_type 0 accommodates 0 bedrooms 3895 beds 441 amenities 0 price_US$ 0 minimum_nights 0 maximum_nights 0 has_availability 0 review_scores_rating 6793 instant_bookable 0 dtype: int64 ``` ::: ::: Some listings have no reviews and an unknown host acceptance rate and host name. Most Airbnb users exclude such listings from their search results. To mimic this filtering approach, we’ll filter out any rows that do not have a `review_scores_rating` and without a ``host_acceptance_rate` and `host_name`. ::: {.cell execution_count=17} ``` {.python .cell-code} hi_listings = hi_listings.dropna( subset=[ "host_name", "host_acceptance_rate", "review_scores_rating" ] ) ``` ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=18} ``` {.python .cell-code} hi_listings.isnull().sum().loc[lambda x : x != 0] ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=18} ``` bedrooms 3200 beds 285 dtype: int64 ``` ::: ::: Let’s make some simple assumptions based on the room_type assigned to the listing. Which room types are found in the dataset. ::: {.cell execution_count=19} ``` {.python .cell-code} hi_listings["room_type"].value_counts() ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=19} ``` Entire home/apt 21191 Private room 1947 Hotel room 61 Shared room 43 Name: room_type, dtype: int64 ``` ::: ::: There are four room types. Let's make the assumption that the columns `bedrooms` and `beds` are potentially influenced by `room_type`. Therefore, we can make the following rules: - If you have a **"Private room"** or **"Shared room"** as `room_type`, then we believe the listing only has one bedroom. - If the listing has **"Hotel room"** or **"Entire home/apt"** as `room_type`, then we can divide the number of guests the listing accomodates by 2 and round up. - If any of these numbers are missing, then we can leave it empty. Translate these requirements into a Python function, and you get: ::: {.cell execution_count=20} ``` {.python .cell-code} def fill_empty_bedrooms(accommodates: int, bedrooms: int, room_type: str) -> int: if (room_type == "Private room") or (room_type == "Shared room"): return 1 elif (room_type == "Hotel room") or (room_type == "Entire home/apt"): return np.ceil(accommodates / 2) else: return bedrooms ``` ::: In the case of Pandas, we are using `apply()` to semi-vectorize our function, but secretly this function just implements something that mimics a for loop. Using a `lambda` together with `apply()` allows us to access multiple columns to generate an outcome. This approach is often good enough, but not always, especially if you are dealing with large datasets. Below we will run the `apply()` function for output. ::: {.cell execution_count=21} ``` {.python .cell-code} hi_listings["bedrooms"] = hi_listings[["accommodates", "bedrooms", "room_type"]].apply( lambda x: fill_empty_bedrooms(x["accommodates"], x["bedrooms"], x["room_type"]), axis=1, ) ``` ::: Thanks to our logic and assumptions, most listings now have a proper amount of defined rooms. However, there are still a few listings without any number of rooms defined. Remove all rows/entries that have an empty bedrooms, beds. ::: {.cell execution_count=22} ``` {.python .cell-code} hi_listings[["bedrooms", "beds"]].isnull().sum() ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=22} ``` bedrooms 0 beds 285 dtype: int64 ``` ::: ::: Removing rows with missing value in the `beds` column. ::: {.cell execution_count=23} ``` {.python .cell-code} hi_listings = hi_listings.dropna(subset=["beds"]) ``` ::: Memory usage ::: {.cell execution_count=24} ``` {.python .cell-code} hi_listings.memory_usage(deep=True).sum() ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=24} ``` 4052610 ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=25} ``` {.python .cell-code} hi_listings.neighbourhood_group.value_counts() ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=25} ``` Maui 7549 Honolulu 6360 Hawaii 5628 Kauai 3420 Name: neighbourhood_group, dtype: int64 ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=26} ``` {.python .cell-code} grouped_df = (hi_listings .groupby(["neighbourhood_group", "room_type"]) .size() .reset_index(name="counts") .sort_values(by=["neighbourhood_group","counts"], ascending=(True, False) ) ) grouped_df ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=26} ```{=html}

``` ::: ::: ## Kauai ::: {.cell execution_count=28} ``` {.python .cell-code} kauai_listings = (hi_listings .query('neighbourhood_group == "Kauai"') .drop(columns=["neighbourhood_group"]) ) kauai_listings.info() ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` Int64Index: 3420 entries, 1 to 30745 Data columns (total 18 columns): # Column Non-Null Count Dtype --- ------ -------------- ----- 0 id 3420 non-null int64 1 host_name 3420 non-null object 2 host_acceptance_rate 3420 non-null float64 3 host_is_superhost 3420 non-null bool 4 neighbourhood 3420 non-null category 5 latitude 3420 non-null float64 6 longitude 3420 non-null float64 7 room_type 3420 non-null category 8 accommodates 3420 non-null int64 9 bedrooms 3420 non-null float64 10 beds 3420 non-null float64 11 amenities 3420 non-null int64 12 price_US$ 3420 non-null float64 13 minimum_nights 3420 non-null int64 14 maximum_nights 3420 non-null int64 15 has_availability 3420 non-null bool 16 review_scores_rating 3420 non-null float64 17 instant_bookable 3420 non-null bool dtypes: bool(3), category(2), float64(7), int64(5), object(1) memory usage: 392.2+ KB ``` ::: ::: Save Kauai listings dataframe ::: {.cell execution_count=29} ``` {.python .cell-code} kauai_listings.to_csv("data/kauai_final.csv") ``` ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=30} ``` {.python .cell-code} alt.Chart(kauai_listings, width=500, height=300).mark_bar().encode( x=alt.X('price_US$t:Q', bin=alt.Bin(maxbins=20)), y=alt.Y('count():Q') ).properties(title="Histogram plot") ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=30} ```{=html}
